  "diary": "Started the morning right—good coffee at home, then headed out to catch the Fremont Market before the crowds got too thick. The weather was perfect for wandering, even if overcast. Ran into Marcus and his partner at a produce stand, we laughed about something ridiculous I can't even remember now. Grabbed a second coffee at Ladro and just sat there planning my day, watching the neighborhood wake up around me. The studio was steady—three solid clients back-to-back, including this beautiful mandala piece on a first-timer who was nervous but trusting. Lunch at Taneda was exactly what I needed. By the time I got home, I felt that good tired, you know? Made a stir-fry with the fresh vegetables from the market, settled in with a show, and let the day just... settle. There's something grounding about Saturdays when they flow like this.",
  "thought_process": "I think I needed today to be simple and grounded. The overcast weather actually felt right—not demanding anything from me, just existing. I chose to hit the farmers market early specifically to avoid the Mariners game crowds that would be flooding SoDo; I wanted my morning to feel unhurried. The market always reminds me why I love this city. Work was solid, nothing dramatic, which was perfect. I found myself lingering over the expense spreadsheet and thrifting later because I needed that meditative, low-stakes activity after being \"on\" with clients all afternoon. The fresh produce from this morning made cooking dinner feel like a continuation of something good rather than a chore. My mood stayed even and content—no peaks or valleys, just a day that felt sustainable and real.",
